`scripts/` is the repo's CI/lint enforcement layer, invoked by `ctx-verify`'s check batteries and (for the two doc-generator scripts) by doc-freshness checks — nothing outside this directory calls these scripts directly except through those two integration points.

Every check script (`cycle_check.sh`, `machete_check.sh`, `no_allow_check.sh`, `rationale_check.py`, `retired_terms_check.sh`, `workspace_lints_check.sh`) shares a strict contract: enumerate files via `git ls-files -z --cached --others --exclude-standard` (never a filesystem walk, to avoid racing `target/` writers and to respect `.gitignore`), emit failures as `FAIL: <path>:<line>: message` to stderr, accumulate a `FAIL` flag rather than short-circuiting, and exit 1 if any FAIL was emitted. `retired_terms_check.sh` and `no_allow_check.sh` both rely on appending `/dev/null` to force grep's multi-file `path:line:` prefix even for single-file matches — this is a copy-pasted trick, not a shared helper, so it must be preserved if either script is edited independently. Adding a new banned-term or exemption goes into `retired_terms_check.sh`'s `is_allowed()`/`BANNED` array only, never by loosening a grep pattern.

The two `gen_*` scripts are a different pair: both regenerate a marked block (HTML comment markers) in one or more docs, support `--write` (default, rewrites in place) and `--check` (emits `FAIL:` lines, doesn't modify), and both hard-fail if the markers are missing. `gen_tool_contracts.sh` requires prebuilt `target/debug/` binaries (`ctx-context`, `ctx-verify`, `ctx-scan`, `ctx-cage`, `ctx-brief`) and never invokes cargo; `gen_readme_architecture.sh` consumes `.context/rollup.ctx` directly as the generated artifact. Their `DOCS` target lists are deliberately per-repo (this repo's copy differs from `template/scripts/`) and must not be merged.

`cycle_check.sh` and `rationale_check.py` are both explicit MVP placeholders deferred to future dylint rules (per `docs/DYLINT_RULES.md`) — their heuristics are intentionally weak and callers must not read success as a strong guarantee.